ence on Medievalism, in ever more sessions at the annual International Congress on Medieval Studies, and by many recent or forthcoming publications has left little doubtof the importance of this new, provocative area of study. In response to a seminal essay defining medievalism in relationship to neomedievalism [published in volume 18 of this journal], this book begins with seven essays definingneomedievalism in relationship to medievalism. Their positions are then tested by five articles, whose subjects range from modern American manifestations of Byzantine art, to the Vietnam War as refracted through non-heterosexual implications in the 1976 movie Robin and Marian, and versions of abjection in recent Beowulf films. Theory and practice are thus juxtaposed in a volume that is certain to fuel a central debate in not one but two of the fastest growing areas of academia. Contributors: Amy S. Kaufman, Brent Moberley, Kevin Moberley, Lesley Coote, Cory Lowell Grewell, M.J. Toswell, E.L. Risden, Lauryn S. Mayer, Glenn Peers, Tison Pugh, David W. Marshall,Richard H. Osberg, Richard Utz  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAmy S. Kaufman.  aBeowulf films.  aByzantine art.  aCory Lowell Grewell.  aEarly Modern court.  aKevin Moberley.  aLesley Coote.  aM.J. Toswell.  aNeomedievalism.  aVietnam War.  acompositional process.  amodern American manifestations.  asource studies.1 aCoote, Lesley A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoote, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFugelso, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFugelso, Karl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re